	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1292063">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1292063">
                  
                  <div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Elasto</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">How about judges being voted in by their peers?</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
 <br />
And who starts the process of picking their peers? The current judges were all appointed by a president  no matter how you cut it, you cannot remove politics from the equation entirely. <br />
 <br />
For that matter, why would you want to? We are talking about democratic societies, and while you wouldn't want judges to be subject to every political whim, it's not desirable for them to be so far removed from people that their judgements fail to reflect the practical realities of life. Without the pressure of politics, the United States would never have enacted the social programs now considered an integral part of modern industrial societies. Without the pressure of politics, we might not have desegregated schools. <br />
 <br />
You need a happy medium. I find it hard to see how we can significantly improve on the current system, which forces two legs of government to agree on the members of the third, which, in turn, has a lifelong tenure to guard against overexposure to politics. <br />
 <br />
I do sense that you're arguing for separating prosecutors (i.e., the Justice Department) from the executive branch, but we already have the least political, least biased solution in the form of executive appointment. <br />
 <br />
Consider the alternatives: appointment by the legislature (which only increases the political nature of the position); election by popular vote (the most political solution of all); or appointed by judges (which would be a horrible idea, since judges must be separate as possible from the parties in a case to ensure lack of bias). They would all introduce problems of equal or greater magnitude than the current system.  <br />
 <br />
You can't remove politics from government in a democratic society. And you shouldn't, since that's the whole point of democracy.
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
