@Elasto: I think you're looking for the impossible. There's no basis for a selection that guarantees an unbiased judge. You just can choose <i>which</i> bias you prefer, but it can never be the &quot;spirit of the law&quot;.<br />
<br />
(First reason that comes to mind against meritocracy: popularity, charisma and eloquence, neither of those are a substitute for a &quot;moral compass&quot;, but play a huge factor in meritocracy; i.e. a well-explained bad decision will most likely gain more 'merit' than a badly-explained perfect decision)
                  
